human
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 
\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
nature 
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
itself. (This is a point I return to in the third essay.) Secondly, arguments that ground what we should do in what we actually do often illicitly move from \'91is\'92 to \'91ought\'92. That is, they begin with factual premises and end with evaluative conclusions. \'93People seek happiness, therefore they ought to seek happiness for the greatest number.\'94 This is only licit if we grant one ungrounded evaluative premise, like \'93we ought to do for others what we do for ourselves.\'94 That premise seems to cite a normative fact that is both real and not obviously natural. Thirdly, I agree with Elizabeth Anscombe\'92s criticism that consequentialism is far too open-minded about some actions we already know are wrong. She says it is no use arguing with someone who \'93really thinks, in advance, that it is open to question whether such an action as procuring the judicial execution of the innocent should be quite excluded from consideration.\'94\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
